"""
mkt-christ | 2 Kings 15-17 | fill
Covers missing verses: ch15 (all except v5), ch16 (all except v7), ch17 (all except v13)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2kings-15-17-fill.py
"""
import json, pathlib

def load_comm(path):
    p = pathlib.Path(path)
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(path, data):
    pathlib.Path(path).write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
"15": {
"1": '<p>The theme: Azariah&#8217;s accession continues the Davidic line&#8212;the dynasty God promised would endure (2 Sam 7:16). The synchronism with Jeroboam&#8217;s reign frames two contrasting kingdoms: Israel&#8217;s long-reigning northern king versus Judah&#8217;s covenantally grounded southern king. Where all human dynasties end, Christ&#8217;s reign does not (Luke 1:32&#8211;33).</p>',
"2": '<p>Azariah (Uzziah) reigned fifty-two years&#8212;one of Judah&#8217;s longest reigns. Yet even this long stability ends; only Christ&#8217;s kingdom has no end (Rev 11:15). Azariah&#8217;s extended reign provides a theme of provisional messianic peace, pointing toward the eternal peace of the Son of David (Isa 9:7).</p>',
"3": '<p>The theme: &#8220;did what was right in the sight of the LORD&#8221;&#8212;the covenant fidelity formula applied to Davidic kings. Christ alone satisfies this standard perfectly and permanently (Heb 7:26). The partial obedience of even the best kings underscores the need for the &#8220;Branch of righteousness&#8221; anticipated in Jeremiah 23:5.</p>',
"4": '<p>The theme: the high places persisted even under faithful kings&#8212;the persistent cultic compromise of Judah. Each reform that stops short points to the incompleteness of human renewal. The NT presents Christ as the one who renders all rival altars obsolete (Heb 9:11&#8211;14), replacing the entire sacrificial infrastructure with his once-for-all offering.</p>',
"6": '<p>The theme: the chronicle formula&#8212;&#8220;are they not written in the Book of the Chronicles?&#8221;&#8212;closes each king&#8217;s account with an appeal to the permanent record. The NT presents the final accounting as the day of judgment (Rev 20:12), when all records are opened. Christ bears his people&#8217;s record so that their account is settled in him (Col 2:14).</p>',
"7": '<p>The theme: the father-to-son Davidic succession continues despite Uzziah&#8217;s isolation from leprosy. The genealogical chain is not broken by disease or political difficulty&#8212;it will ultimately reach the one who sits on David&#8217;s throne permanently (Matt 1:9 includes Uzziah in the genealogy of Jesus).</p>',
"8": '<p>The theme: Zechariah son of Jeroboam reigned only six months&#8212;last of Jehu&#8217;s dynasty. The dynastic instability of the northern kingdom measures the distance between Israel&#8217;s throne and the stable Davidic covenant. Every brief, contested northern reign points toward the king whose throne cannot be seized or ended (Ps 89:3&#8211;4; Acts 2:30).</p>',
"9": '<p>The shadow: &#8220;he did not turn from the sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat&#8212;who had made Israel to sin.&#8221; This cumulative formula across the northern kings functions as a theological verdict: the entire dynasty lived in bondage to the false worship Jeroboam established. The NT addresses this root: Christ&#8217;s redemption breaks not just behavioral patterns but the power of ingrained sin (Rom 6:6&#8211;7).</p>',
"10": '<p>The shadow: political assassination marks the end of Zechariah&#8217;s reign. The cycle of violent succession in Israel contrasts with the Davidic covenant that guarantees continuity in Judah. The NT presents Christ as the legitimate king appointed by God (Acts 2:36), not seizing power by violence but receiving it as the Father&#8217;s gift (Phil 2:9).</p>',
"11": '<p>The theme: another chronicle formula closes another abbreviated, violent reign. The brevity of Zechariah&#8217;s six months underscores the instability of kingship without covenant grounding. The full picture of faithful kingship awaits the Son of David who reigns not for six months but forever (Heb 1:8).</p>',
"12": '<p>A direct prophetic fulfillment: God had promised Jehu that his dynasty would endure to the fourth generation (2 Kgs 10:30), and with Zechariah it ends exactly there. This precision signals that God&#8217;s Word governs history. The greater promise&#8212;that David&#8217;s throne would endure forever (2 Sam 7:16)&#8212;is equally certain and finds its fulfillment in Christ (Acts 13:22&#8211;23).</p>',
"13": '<p>The theme: Shallum reigned one month before being killed&#8212;the most ephemeral of Israel&#8217;s kings. The extreme brevity of his reign measures the depth of the northern kingdom&#8217;s political decay. These broken reigns collectively testify to what lasting kingship requires: a king who cannot be overthrown, ruling by divine right rather than force (Dan 7:14).</p>',
"14": '<p>The shadow: Menahem&#8217;s conspiracy and violence continues the pattern of dynastic illegitimacy in Israel. The kingdom established by Jeroboam&#8217;s rebellion never develops stable succession. The contrast with the Davidic covenant is deliberate: in Judah, God protects the promised line. Christ inherits a covenant throne that violence cannot seize or destroy (John 18:36).</p>',
"15": '<p>The theme: the chronicle formula names Shallum&#8217;s legacy as &#8220;the conspiracy he carried out&#8221;&#8212;not a reign but a usurpation. Every throne seized by violence forfeits the legitimacy that only covenantal appointment provides. The theological trajectory points toward the king whose enthronement comes through the Father&#8217;s decree, not human scheming (Ps 2:6&#8211;7).</p>',
"16": '<p>The shadow: Menahem&#8217;s extreme violence against Tiphsah&#8212;ripping open pregnant women&#8212;signals how far Israel has fallen from the covenant vision of justice and care for the vulnerable. The contrast points forward to Christ, who does not destroy the vulnerable but heals and gathers (Matt 12:20; Isa 42:3). The destruction wrought by failed kings is reversed by the true King who gives life.</p>',
"17": '<p>The theme: Menahem&#8217;s ten-year reign represents relative stability purchased through tribute to Assyria. His rule is propped up by foreign power rather than covenant faithfulness&#8212;a pattern Judah will repeat under Ahaz (ch. 16). The contrast: Christ&#8217;s kingdom needs no foreign backer; his authority comes from the Father alone (Matt 28:18).</p>',
"18": '<p>The shadow: Menahem repeats Jeroboam&#8217;s sin despite a decade of reign. The persistence of Israel&#8217;s idolatry across administrations signals that the problem is deeper than bad leadership&#8212;it is the condition of the heart. The new covenant in Christ promises transformed allegiance from the inside out (Jer 31:33; Heb 8:10), not merely better external compliance.</p>',
"19": '<p>The shadow: Menahem pays tribute to Tiglath-pileser (Pul) to secure his grip on power&#8212;the first formal Assyrian domination of Israel. Israel trades covenant independence for imperial patronage. The NT addresses the deeper bondage this mirrors: humanity enslaved to powers that demand tribute. Christ&#8217;s redemption is a ransom that sets free from a greater bondage (Mark 10:45; 1 Tim 2:6).</p>',
"20": '<p>The theme: the resources of God&#8217;s people are extracted to serve a foreign empire. The economic exploitation of Israel for Assyrian purposes is the bitter fruit of the covenant&#8217;s abandonment. The NT presents Christ&#8217;s kingdom as a counter-economy: the poor are lifted up (Luke 1:52&#8211;53; 4:18) and tribute flows to God, not to empire.</p>',
"21": '<p>The theme: Menahem&#8217;s account closes with the chronicle formula. His legacy: ten years of Assyrian vassalage and Jeroboam-pattern idolatry. The final accounting before Christ (Heb 4:13; Rev 20:12) assesses what the chronicles record and what they do not&#8212;the motivations of the heart behind each act.</p>',
"22": '<p>The theme: Menahem&#8217;s death and Pekahiah&#8217;s accession by father-to-son succession is structurally unusual for the northern kingdom&#8212;most transitions involved assassination. The temporary stability of dynastic succession points toward the Davidic pattern, which would ultimately produce the one whose reign is not interrupted by death (Rev 1:18).</p>',
"23": '<p>The theme: another brief northern reign (two years), another echo of the instability characterizing Israel&#8217;s monarchy without covenant grounding. The LORD&#8217;s promise was to David&#8217;s house; every year of Israel&#8217;s chaotic rule is a negative witness to what that promise means&#8212;and to what Christ, as its fulfillment, provides permanently.</p>',
"24": '<p>The shadow: the theological verdict on Pekahiah is identical to his predecessors&#8212;the same sins of Jeroboam. The formula is not monotonous but cumulative judgment: the northern kingdom never broke the cycle. This intergenerational bondage to false worship is what the new covenant in Christ addresses at the root&#8212;a transformed heart, not merely better conduct (Ezek 36:26&#8211;27).</p>',
"25": '<p>The shadow: Pekah&#8217;s military conspiracy ends Pekahiah&#8217;s reign. The cycle of violence consuming Israel&#8217;s leadership points forward to Christ&#8217;s diagnosis: those who live by the sword perish by the sword (Matt 26:52). The kingdom that endures is not built by violence but by the cross&#8212;where power is exercised through willing self-giving, not seizure.</p>',
"26": '<p>The theme: Pekahiah&#8217;s two-year reign is notable only for its end. The chronicle formula closes his brief account. The pattern of abbreviated, violent northern reigns serves as a sustained argument: human kingship without covenant faithfulness cannot sustain itself. The one king whose account never closes is the eternal king whose name is written in the Lamb&#8217;s book of life (Rev 21:27).</p>',
"27": '<p>The theme: Pekah&#8217;s twenty-year reign&#8212;longer than most northern kings&#8212;brings no spiritual change and ultimately ends with Assyria taking the northern territories (v29). External stability without internal renewal is not salvation. Christ brings the renewal that makes lasting peace possible&#8212;not merely a longer reign but an eternal kingdom (Dan 7:14; Rev 11:15).</p>',
"28": '<p>The shadow: the theological formula applies identically to Pekah after twenty years. This persistent idolatry across two decades points to the depth of the problem&#8212;not a failure of individual will but a structural bondage requiring the kind of redemption only Christ provides. Paul&#8217;s language of being &#8220;freed from sin&#8221; (Rom 6:18) addresses what these repeated assessments diagnose.</p>',
"29": '<p>A shadow with direct NT fulfillment: Tiglath-pileser captures the Galilean and Transjordan territories, deporting their populations to Assyria. Isaiah 9:1 explicitly names this darkness: &#8220;the land of Zebulun and the land of Naphtali... Galilee of the nations&#8212;the people walking in darkness have seen a great light.&#8221; Matthew 4:15&#8211;16 identifies Jesus&#8217; Galilean ministry as the fulfillment of that promise. The desolation Tiglath-pileser creates is the specific darkness into which Christ&#8217;s light shines.</p>',
"30": '<p>The shadow: Hoshea&#8217;s assassination of Pekah ends the last significant northern dynasty. The violence that marked Israel&#8217;s throne from Jeroboam onward reaches its terminal stage; Hoshea will be the last king. The arc from Jeroboam&#8217;s rebellion to this final assassination measures what covenant infidelity produces. Christ, unlike every king before him, is killed by conspirators&#8212;but his death does not end his reign (Rev 1:18).</p>',
"31": '<p>The theme: Pekah&#8217;s account closes with the standard formula, but his lasting legacy is the loss of the northern territories to Assyria. Human achievement leaves behind records of territory lost; Christ&#8217;s work leaves behind not territories lost but people redeemed, a kingdom that cannot be shaken (Heb 12:28).</p>',
"32": '<p>The theme: Jotham&#8217;s accession in Judah while Israel convulses through assassinations signals the covenant contrast between the kingdoms. The Davidic line continues through orderly succession&#8212;covenantally grounded even when imperfect. Matthew 1:9 lists Jotham in the genealogy of Jesus: each Davidic accession is a link in the chain that reaches Christ.</p>',
"33": '<p>The theme: Jotham&#8217;s sixteen-year reign places him among Judah&#8217;s longer-tenured kings and in Isaiah&#8217;s historical context (Isa 1:1). Each Judahite king in this lineage is a link in the genealogical chain preserved by God despite surrounding chaos. Matthew 1:9 lists Jotham explicitly in the ancestry of Christ.</p>',
"34": '<p>The theme: Jotham &#8220;did what was right&#8221;&#8212;the positive formula distinguishing him from the northern kings. Yet even the best Judahite kings are partial and incomplete (the high places remain, v35). The contrast with Christ&#8212;who is described as &#8220;faithful and true&#8221; (Rev 19:11) and who fulfilled all righteousness (Matt 3:15)&#8212;shows what the formula is pointing toward.</p>',
"35": '<p>The shadow: Jotham builds the upper gate of the temple but cannot complete the cultic reform; the high places remain. Construction on God&#8217;s house alongside persistent rival worship mirrors the divided loyalty even faithful kings cannot overcome. Christ builds a different kind of house&#8212;the church&#8212;in which he himself is the cornerstone (Eph 2:20&#8211;22), with no rival altars permitted.</p>',
"36": '<p>The theme: Jotham&#8217;s account closes with the chronicle formula. He is noted positively but briefly&#8212;a king who did right but did not finish the reform. The full assessment of what his reign meant awaits the judgment where not merely external acts but inward motivations are examined (1 Cor 4:5; Rev 20:12).</p>',
"37": '<p>A revelation of God with direct prophetic significance: &#8220;In those days the LORD began to send Rezin and Pekah against Judah.&#8221; This is the opening of the Syro-Ephraimite crisis, the historical context for Isaiah 7 and the Emmanuel prophecy (Isa 7:14). The political pressure God orchestrates on Judah becomes the occasion for one of the most direct prophecies of Christ&#8217;s birth in the entire OT&#8212;cited by Matthew at the nativity (Matt 1:23).</p>',
"38": '<p>The theme: Jotham&#8217;s death and Ahaz&#8217;s accession is one of the sharpest transitions in Judah&#8217;s history&#8212;from a relatively faithful king to one of Judah&#8217;s worst. Yet even Ahaz is a link in the genealogical chain leading to Christ (Matt 1:9). The Davidic covenant&#8217;s preservation through unfaithful kings demonstrates that it rests on divine commitment, not human merit.</p>'
},
"16": {
"1": '<p>The theme: Ahaz&#8217;s accession places him at the height of the Syro-Ephraimite crisis. Isaiah&#8217;s ministry begins here; the Emmanuel prophecy (Isa 7:14) is given to Ahaz himself. The narrative shows Ahaz rejecting the prophetic offer of faith and turning to Assyria instead&#8212;the exact context in which God announces that he himself will give the sign of a virgin-born son (Matt 1:23).</p>',
"2": '<p>The shadow: unlike any other Judahite evaluation, Ahaz is explicitly compared to David&#8212;and falls short. &#8220;He did not do what was right... as David his ancestor had done.&#8221; David is the covenant standard; Ahaz is its antithesis. This comparison sets up the need for the son of David who fulfills what David only partially modeled: the king who is righteous through and through (Jer 23:5&#8211;6; 2 Cor 5:21).</p>',
"3": '<p>The shadow: Ahaz made his son &#8220;pass through the fire&#8212;following the abominable practices of the nations the LORD had expelled.&#8221; This child sacrifice stands as the dark mirror-image of the Father who gives his own Son (John 3:16; Rom 8:32). What Ahaz does to his son in service of Molech, the Father does with his Son in service of love&#8212;but the Son consents and the sacrifice is not for judgment but for redemption.</p>',
"4": '<p>The theme: Ahaz worships at every high place&#8212;on hills, under spreading trees. The ubiquity of his false worship reflects the complete breakdown of covenant exclusivity. The contrast: Christ fulfills and replaces the geographic specificity of Israel&#8217;s worship by becoming himself the universal meeting point between humanity and God (John 4:21&#8211;24; 14:6).</p>',
"5": '<p>A revelation of God: the Syro-Ephraimite coalition besieges Jerusalem but cannot take it. Isaiah 7:7 declares: &#8220;This will not take place.&#8221; The LORD protects Jerusalem not because Ahaz deserves it but because the Davidic covenant guarantees the city until the Son of David arrives. God&#8217;s maintenance of his promise despite Ahaz&#8217;s faithlessness points to the security Christ provides: his covenant holds even when his people are unfaithful (2 Tim 2:13).</p>',
"6": '<p>The theme: while Jerusalem is spared, Syria recovers Elath and expels the Judeans there&#8212;a territorial loss showing that partial judgment accompanies disobedience even when total destruction is withheld by grace. The NT pattern matches: those in Christ are not condemned (Rom 8:1), yet the process of sanctification involves real discipline (Heb 12:5&#8211;11).</p>',
"8": '<p>The shadow: Ahaz strips the temple of silver and gold to fund an Assyrian alliance&#8212;sacred wealth dedicated to God&#8217;s house becomes tribute to a pagan king. Christ drives out those who have commercialized the temple (John 2:14&#8211;16) and gives his own body as the true temple (John 2:21). The plundering of the sacred for political security is the pattern Christ reverses.</p>',
"9": '<p>The theme: the LORD uses Assyria as his instrument to destroy Damascus, while these same instruments will later judge Israel. The divine economy behind Assyria&#8217;s power&#8212;&#8220;the rod of my anger&#8221; (Isa 10:5)&#8212;points toward the NT understanding that all earthly powers ultimately serve divine sovereignty (Rom 13:1; Acts 4:27&#8211;28)&#8212;a sovereignty fully expressed in Christ.</p>',
"10": '<p>The shadow: Ahaz sees the Damascus altar and has it copied for Jerusalem&#8212;importing pagan worship infrastructure into God&#8217;s house. The sacred space is remade in the image of a conquered enemy&#8217;s religion. The shadow points forward to Revelation 21:22: the new Jerusalem needs no temple because God and the Lamb are its temple. All Ahaz-style substitutions are permanently ended in the new creation.</p>',
"11": '<p>The theme: Urijah the priest complies with the king&#8217;s idolatrous command&#8212;priestly authority subordinated to royal politics. The corruption of the priesthood under pressure is a persistent theme in Kings. The contrast: Christ is both king and priest in the order of Melchizedek (Heb 7:1&#8211;3), and in him neither office corrupts the other. No earthly king can command the high priest Christ to substitute a foreign altar for the true one.</p>',
"12": '<p>The shadow: Ahaz &#8220;approached it and mounted it&#8221;&#8212;personally inaugurating the pagan altar as the new meeting place with God. The altar is the place where humanity and God meet through sacrifice. All OT altars point toward Christ&#8212;simultaneously priest, altar, and sacrifice (Heb 13:10; 9:14). Ahaz&#8217;s false altar is the antithesis of this true meeting place.</p>',
"13": '<p>The shadow: Ahaz performs the full sacrificial ritual on the foreign altar&#8212;burnt offering, grain offering, drink offering, peace offering. The liturgical forms are preserved while the covenant reality is perverted. This inverted worship is what Christ condemns as worship &#8220;in vain&#8221; (Mark 7:7). True worship is &#8220;in spirit and truth&#8221; (John 4:23), possible only through Christ&#8217;s mediation&#8212;not through the right form applied to the wrong altar.</p>',
"14": '<p>The shadow: Ahaz moves the bronze Solomonic altar&#8212;the altar placed before the LORD&#8212;to one side, demoting it. The true altar of Israel is pushed aside to make room for a pagan substitute. The NT inversion is complete: Christ the true altar makes all lesser altars obsolete (Heb 10:9&#8211;10). The displaced bronze altar prefigures the entire OT sacrificial system, itself displaced by the cross.</p>',
"15": '<p>The theme: Ahaz directs that the new altar handle all official sacrifices while the bronze altar is reserved only for his personal inquiry. The royal takeover of the priestly function violates the covenantal separation of throne and altar. Christ alone holds both roles legitimately (Heb 7:14&#8211;17)&#8212;as king and priest in the order of Melchizedek, with no conflict between the two.</p>',
"16": '<p>The theme: &#8220;Urijah the priest did everything King Ahaz commanded.&#8221; Unconditional compliance with idolatrous royal commands represents the corruption of the prophetic-priestly check on royal power. True priesthood cannot be subordinated to royal politics. The contrast: the high priest Christ does not comply with the demands of earthly rulers but intercedes before God according to his own eternal and uncompromised office (Heb 7:24&#8211;25).</p>',
"17": '<p>The shadow: Ahaz systematically dismantles the temple furnishings&#8212;the bronze sea, the wheeled stands&#8212;for tribute to Assyria. Solomon&#8217;s temple is being disassembled under royal faithlessness. Christ&#8217;s declaration that he would rebuild the destroyed temple in three days (John 2:19) addresses this entire trajectory of desacralization, promising that what human unfaithfulness destroys, divine power restores permanently.</p>',
"18": '<p>The shadow: Ahaz alters the temple entrance &#8220;because of the king of Assyria.&#8221; Even the architecture of worship is remade to appease foreign power. The NT contrast: the church, Christ&#8217;s body, is not remade to accommodate empire but remains oriented toward Christ as its head (Eph 1:22&#8211;23), regardless of external political pressure. What Ahaz did to the physical temple, no one can do to the living temple Christ is building.</p>',
"19": '<p>The theme: Ahaz&#8217;s account closes with the chronicle formula, but his legacy is the dismantled temple, the imported altar, the child sacrifice, and the Assyrian alliance. The chronicle records it all. The judgment before Christ assesses everything done in the body, whether good or evil (2 Cor 5:10)&#8212;Ahaz&#8217;s full account included.</p>',
"20": '<p>The theme: Ahaz&#8217;s death and Hezekiah&#8217;s accession is one of the most significant transitions in Kings. Hezekiah is the most explicitly Christological of the Judahite kings&#8212;a type of Christ in his trust of God against impossible odds, his illness and miraculous recovery (Isa 38), and his concern for God&#8217;s temple. That such a king follows the disastrous Ahaz shows that God&#8217;s purposes are not defeated by human faithlessness&#8212;a principle Christ himself embodies after the failure of all human kings.</p>'
},
"17": {
"1": '<p>The theme: Hoshea son of Elah is the last king of Israel. His accession frames the simultaneous decline of both kingdoms. The northern kingdom&#8217;s monarchy, which began with Jeroboam&#8217;s rebellion against the Davidic covenant, ends with Hoshea. The contrast with the Davidic line&#8212;which continues despite all pressure&#8212;measures the difference between a kingdom built on human rebellion and one built on divine promise. Christ inherits the Davidic covenant; there is no successor to Jeroboam&#8217;s.</p>',
"2": '<p>The theme: the qualified verdict&#8212;&#8220;not to the degree of the kings before him&#8221;&#8212;is unique among northern king evaluations. But mitigation does not prevent judgment: Hoshea&#8217;s lesser evil still leads to exile. The theme points to the insufficiency of comparative righteousness. The NT makes this explicit: all have sinned and fall short (Rom 3:23); the only comparison that matters is against Christ&#8217;s perfect obedience (2 Cor 5:21).</p>',
"3": '<p>The theme: the last king of Israel is immediately subjugated&#8212;a vassal paying tribute. The entire northern kingdom, once a regional power, is now a subject state. The theme of political subjugation as the fruit of covenant unfaithfulness runs throughout Kings. Christ enters a world similarly subjected&#8212;Judea under Rome&#8212;and addresses its root cause: subjugation to sin and death (John 8:34&#8211;36).</p>',
"4": '<p>The shadow: Hoshea turns to Egypt for deliverance from Assyria&#8212;the same Egypt that Israel had been redeemed from at the Exodus. This is the final irony of the northern kingdom: seeking salvation from the very power God once overthrew to establish the nation. The shadow points to the universal human tendency to seek redemption from failed sources. Christ is the one who fulfills what Egypt once represented (Matt 2:15; Hos 11:1), providing the true and final exodus.</p>',
"5": '<p>The theme: the three-year siege signals both the strength of Samaria&#8217;s defenses and the inevitability of its fall. No human fortification can ultimately resist the judgment that covenant unfaithfulness has invited. God&#8217;s patience in allowing a three-year siege mirrors his patience in history: not weakness but the window for repentance (2 Pet 3:9). Christ&#8217;s patience in calling Israel through the prophets was exhausted for the northern kingdom&#8212;but not exhausted in Christ himself toward any who will turn (Matt 23:37).</p>',
"6": '<p>A major shadow: the fall of Samaria in 722 BCE is the theological climax of the northern kingdom&#8217;s story. The loss of the land promised to Abraham (Gen 12:7) is the covenant&#8217;s judgment in historical form. Yet the NT declares that the return from exile is not complete until Christ gathers his people &#8220;from the four winds&#8221; (Matt 24:31; Isa 11:11&#8211;12). The Assyrian deportation is the shadow of the universal exile from which Christ is the ultimate exodus.</p>',
"7": '<p>The revelation of God: &#8220;This happened because the Israelites had sinned against the LORD their God, who had brought them out of Egypt.&#8221; The Exodus is invoked to measure the magnitude of the ingratitude&#8212;the greatest salvation in Israel&#8217;s history undone by sustained covenant-breaking. The NT counterpart warns those who have experienced the greater exodus in Christ (1 Cor 10:1&#8211;4) against the same pattern of turning away (Heb 3:12&#8211;19).</p>',
"8": '<p>The shadow: Israel &#8220;followed the practices of the nations the LORD had driven out.&#8221; The irony is absolute: Israel was given the land because the Canaanites were expelled for their abominations; now Israel does the same and faces the same expulsion. The same God applies the same standard to his own people as to the nations (Rom 11:20&#8211;22). Christ bore the covenant curse (Gal 3:13) so that his people might not be expelled as Israel was.</p>',
"9": '<p>The shadow: Israel &#8220;secretly did things against the LORD&#8212;from watchtower to fortified city.&#8221; The comprehensive and covert nature of their idolatry reveals a systemic problem, not isolated apostasy. The NT addresses the secret life that no human chronicle records: Christ&#8217;s judgment examines hidden things (1 Cor 4:5) and the heart&#8217;s secret motivations (Heb 4:12&#8211;13), precisely what Israel&#8217;s secret worship concealed.</p>',
"10": '<p>The shadow: pillars and Asherah poles on every high hill and under every tree&#8212;the entire landscape of Canaan now colonized by Israel&#8217;s own idolatry. The visual description is a theological verdict: Israel has become what it was called to displace. The NT points to the new creation (2 Cor 5:17; Rev 21:1&#8211;5) in which the landscape colonized by idolatry is reconstituted as a creation fully consecrated to God.</p>',
"11": '<p>The shadow: Israel burned incense at the high places &#8220;as the nations did&#8212;nations the LORD had expelled.&#8221; The comparison to expelled nations completes the indictment: Israel has become Canaan. The true incense&#8212;the prayers of the saints (Rev 5:8; 8:3&#8211;4)&#8212;rises to God through Christ&#8217;s mediation at the right altar. Where Israel&#8217;s incense rises at wrong altars, Christ provides the true meeting point.</p>',
"12": '<p>The shadow: &#8220;They served idols, despite the LORD&#8217;s explicit prohibition.&#8221; The simplicity of this verse is its indictment: they knew exactly what God commanded and chose the opposite. The NT diagnoses this as the universal human condition (Rom 1:18&#8211;23)&#8212;knowing God but refusing to honor him. The grace that addresses willful covenant-breaking is the grace of the cross, where Christ bore the penalty of those who served what they knew was not God.</p>',
"14": '<p>The shadow: Israel &#8220;was as stubborn as their ancestors who had not trusted in the LORD their God.&#8221; The intergenerational stubbornness is covenantally significant&#8212;each generation inheriting and amplifying the pattern of the previous. The NT diagnoses this as the hardened heart (Heb 3:7&#8211;11, citing Ps 95). Christ&#8217;s work addresses the root condition: the hard heart that will not believe is transformed by the Spirit Christ sends (John 16:7&#8211;8; Ezek 36:26).</p>',
"15": '<p>A revelation of God: &#8220;They rejected his statutes and the covenant he had made with their ancestors, along with the warnings he had given them.&#8221; Covenant rejection is not passive neglect but active repudiation. The accumulated prophetic warnings were specific, sustained, and personal; Israel rejected all of them. Christ is the mediator of a new covenant (Heb 9:15) that addresses this rejection at the root&#8212;providing the obedience Israel could not supply (2 Cor 1:20; Rom 5:19).</p>',
"16": '<p>The shadow: the inventory of Israel&#8217;s idolatry&#8212;golden calves, Asherah pole, star worship&#8212;covers every major category of ancient Near Eastern religion. The host-of-heaven worship is particularly significant: the NT presents Christ as the one whose coming de-mythologizes the heavenly powers&#8212;the &#8220;rulers and authorities&#8221; are disarmed at the cross (Col 2:15), and the host of heaven becomes the choir declaring his glory (Rev 5:11&#8211;12), not objects of cult.</p>',
"17": '<p>The shadow: &#8220;They burned their sons and daughters in the fire, practiced divination and sorcery, and gave themselves over completely to doing what was evil.&#8221; These are the practices God condemned in the expelled nations (Deut 18:10&#8211;12). The contrast: God himself gives his own Son (John 3:16)&#8212;not to appease a false god&#8217;s hunger but to satisfy divine justice and rescue humanity. The true sacrifice Christ offers reverses the logic of all false ones.</p>',
"18": '<p>A revelation of God: &#8220;So the LORD was extremely angry with Israel and expelled them from his sight.&#8221; To be expelled from the LORD&#8217;s sight is the inverse of the covenant promise: &#8220;I will be your God and you will be my people.&#8221; The exile is relational before it is geographical. Christ on the cross experiences the ultimate expulsion&#8212;&#8220;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&#8221; (Matt 27:46)&#8212;bearing in his own person the God-forsakenness that Israel&#8217;s sin deserved (2 Cor 5:21).</p>',
"19": '<p>The shadow: &#8220;Judah also did not obey the commands of the LORD their God but followed the practices Israel had introduced.&#8221; The southern kingdom&#8217;s guilt is noted in the context of the northern exile&#8212;a warning that the same judgment awaits Judah if it persists. Israel&#8217;s fall is a mirror and warning for the whole covenant community. The NT generalizes this: all have sinned (Rom 3:23); the exile is the specific historical form of a universal condition that Christ addresses at the root.</p>',
"20": '<p>A revelation of God: &#8220;The LORD rejected all the descendants of Israel, afflicted them, and handed them over to raiders, until he had expelled them from his sight.&#8221; This summary verdict covers the entire northern kingdom from Jeroboam onward. The NT counterpoint: &#8220;God did not reject his people whom he foreknew&#8221; (Rom 11:2), because Christ bears the rejection that Israel&#8217;s unfaithfulness earned, and through him a remnant is preserved and ultimately restored (Rom 11:25&#8211;26).</p>',
"21": '<p>A revelation of God: &#8220;When Israel was torn away from the house of David, they made Jeroboam son of Nebat king.&#8221; The root of the northern kingdom&#8217;s failure is here&#8212;the rejection of the Davidic line. Every sin of the northern kings traces back to this foundational act. As Israel rejected the Davidic line and sealed its doom, humanity&#8217;s rejection of the Son of David is the ultimate act of covenant betrayal&#8212;which Christ&#8217;s resurrection reverses (Acts 2:36).</p>',
"22": '<p>The shadow: &#8220;The Israelites continued in all the sins Jeroboam had committed; they never turned away from them.&#8221; The word &#8220;never&#8221; marks the theological conclusion: two centuries to repent, and they chose not to. The NT presents the same tragic possibility alongside the same persistent offer: Christ&#8217;s patience endures but is not unconditional&#8212;&#8220;Today, if you hear his voice, do not harden your hearts&#8221; (Heb 3:15).</p>',
"23": '<p>A revelation of God: &#8220;Until the LORD removed Israel from his sight, just as he had declared through all his servants the prophets.&#8221; The exile fulfills prophetic declaration&#8212;the negative fulfillment corresponding to the positive restorations also announced. Christ is the one in whom all prophetic declarations&#8212;judgment and restoration alike&#8212;find their final resolution (2 Cor 1:20). The prophets who announced exile also announced the new covenant (Jer 31:31&#8211;34; Ezek 36:24&#8211;27); Christ fulfills both strands.</p>',
"24": '<p>The theme: the Assyrian policy of population replacement fills the emptied northern territory with peoples from Babylon, Cuthah, Avva, Hamath, and Sepharvaim&#8212;the ancestors of the Samaritans known in Jesus&#8217; day. The theme is significant for the NT: Christ&#8217;s engagement with the Samaritan woman (John 4) takes place in this geographically mixed land, and he explicitly offers living water to one who represents a people excluded from full covenant standing. The Samaritan mission in Acts 8 fulfills Christ&#8217;s own declaration (Acts 1:8).</p>',
"25": '<p>The revelation of God: the new settlers did not worship the LORD, so he sends lions among them&#8212;a sign that the land is holy and its God requires acknowledgment. The LORD&#8217;s claim on the land of Israel extends beyond the covenant people to all who inhabit it. The NT counterpart: God&#8217;s universal sovereignty means all people everywhere are accountable to him (Acts 17:30). Christ&#8217;s gospel goes to every nation (Matt 28:18&#8211;19), claiming the universal lordship that always belonged to him.</p>',
"26": '<p>The theme: &#8220;The peoples you deported do not know the requirements of the god of the land.&#8221; The settlers frame the LORD as a territorial deity&#8212;one god among many. This is the polytheistic misunderstanding that underlies Samaritan religion for centuries. Jesus addresses it directly in John 4:22: &#8220;You Samaritans worship what you do not know.&#8221; The incomplete knowledge this verse describes is precisely what Christ comes to correct.</p>',
"27": '<p>The theme: a displaced Israelite priest is sent back to teach the new settlers how to worship the LORD&#8212;but he settles in Bethel (v28), site of Jeroboam&#8217;s golden calf. The instruction in the LORD&#8217;s worship is mediated through the very site of Israel&#8217;s original apostasy: corrupted instruction giving the form without the substance. Christ is the true teacher who brings not corrupted instruction but the full revelation of the Father (John 14:6&#8211;9).</p>',
"28": '<p>The shadow: the returned priest teaches at Bethel&#8212;Jeroboam&#8217;s cult site of the golden calf. Instruction in &#8220;how to worship the LORD&#8221; is routed through the center of Israel&#8217;s apostasy. This syncretic worship at its origin point is what Jesus addresses when he tells the Samaritan woman that true worship of the Father is &#8220;in spirit and truth&#8221; (John 4:23)&#8212;not tied to Bethel or Jerusalem. The corruption introduced here is finally addressed at its root in Christ.</p>',
"29": '<p>The theme: each national group brings its gods into the former Israelite land&#8212;Babylonian, Cuthean, Hamathite. The resulting landscape is a patchwork of idolatries overlaid on Jeroboam&#8217;s. The theme of idols filling a spiritual vacuum points to Christ&#8217;s warning: when the unclean spirit departs and finds the house empty, it returns with seven others (Matt 12:43&#8211;45). The remedy is not expulsion of false gods but the filling presence of God&#8217;s Spirit&#8212;what Christ sends (John 14:16&#8211;17).</p>',
"30": '<p>The theme: the specific names&#8212;Succoth-benoth (Babylonian astral deity), Nergal (Cuthean underworld deity)&#8212;represent the full range of ancient Near Eastern religion: celestial and chthonic worship. The NT declares these so-called gods are &#8220;no gods at all&#8221; (1 Cor 8:4&#8211;5), while acknowledging demonic powers stand behind them (1 Cor 10:20). Christ&#8217;s triumph over these powers is declared at the cross (Col 2:15)&#8212;the catalogue of foreign gods is answered by the name above every name (Phil 2:9&#8211;11).</p>',
"31": '<p>The shadow: the Sepharvites burned their children to Adrammelech and Anammelech&#8212;continuing in Samaria the very practice that caused Israel&#8217;s original expulsion. The land stained by child sacrifice is now stained again by the new settlers. The contrast: the God who gives his Son freely (John 3:16) and who declared no human should be sacrificed to him (Jer 32:35) sends Christ as the one sacrifice that ends the logic of child sacrifice entirely (Heb 10:14).</p>',
"32": '<p>The shadow: the settlers &#8220;also worshiped the LORD&#8221; while maintaining their national cults&#8212;the classic pattern of religious syncretism. The form of Israelite religion is adopted while the exclusive claim of Israel&#8217;s God is rejected. This is the pattern Christ specifically addresses: no one can serve two masters (Matt 6:24). The Samaritans&#8217; mixed religion is the background against which Jesus&#8217; declaration of exclusive truth (John 14:6) takes its full meaning.</p>',
"33": '<p>The shadow: &#8220;They worshiped the LORD, but they also served their own gods in the way of the nations from which they had come.&#8221; This explicit divided loyalty defines the Samaritan religious identity that persisted for centuries. When Jesus reveals himself to the Samaritan woman as the Messiah (John 4:25&#8211;26), he offers the alternative to divided loyalty&#8212;worship of the Father &#8220;in spirit and truth&#8221; that transcends both Samaritan syncretism and Jewish exclusivism (John 4:21&#8211;24).</p>',
"34": '<p>The theme: &#8220;to this day they follow their original practices. They do not truly fear the LORD.&#8221; The narrator&#8217;s contemporary note signals that the Samaritan condition he describes is a living reality at the time of writing. This is the &#8220;to this day&#8221; syncretism that Jesus encounters in John 4 when he offers a transformation that replaces inadequate knowledge of God with the full revelation of the Father through the Son (John 14:6&#8211;9). &#8220;Salvation is from the Jews&#8221; (John 4:22) begins to address what &#8220;to this day&#8221; has gotten wrong.</p>',
"35": '<p>The theme: the direct covenant command&#8212;&#8220;You must not worship other gods or bow down to them or serve them or sacrifice to them&#8221;&#8212;is the first commandment in its full covenantal force, cited within a narrative of its complete violation. The citation of the original requirement within the story of its abandonment measures the gap between command and conduct. The NT presents Christ as the one who fulfilled every covenant requirement (Matt 5:17) and who enables his people to worship the Father exclusively through his mediation (1 Tim 2:5).</p>',
"36": '<p>The revelation of God: the covenant appeal grounds exclusive worship in the Exodus&#8212;&#8220;the LORD your God, who brought you out of Egypt with great power and an outstretched arm.&#8221; The redemptive act defines both the relationship and the obligation. The NT grounds exclusive worship in the greater exodus: Christ, by his death and resurrection, brought his people out of greater slavery (1 Cor 5:7&#8211;8; 1 Pet 1:18&#8211;19). The appeal &#8220;fear the LORD who redeemed you&#8221; is now grounded in the cross rather than in Egypt, but the structure is identical.</p>',
"37": '<p>The theme: &#8220;You shall carefully observe forever the statutes, ordinances, laws, and commandments he wrote for you.&#8221; The word &#8220;forever&#8221; marks the covenant as a permanent obligation, not a temporary arrangement. The new covenant in Christ fulfills this permanence: the law written on the heart (Jer 31:33) is not a lower standard but a higher one, internalized rather than external. Those in Christ fulfill the law&#8217;s righteous requirement through the Spirit (Rom 8:4).</p>',
"38": '<p>The theme: &#8220;Do not forget the covenant I have made with you.&#8221; Covenant forgetting is the root of Israel&#8217;s idolatry throughout Kings&#8212;not intellectual amnesia but the willful displacement of the covenant relationship. The NT counterpart: the Lord&#8217;s Supper is the covenant memorial meal Christ institutes (Luke 22:19)&#8212;&#8220;do this in remembrance of me.&#8221; Where Israel forgot the covenant through idolatry, Christ gives the new covenant community a specific, embodied act of remembrance that keeps his sacrifice at the center of its life.</p>',
"39": '<p>The revelation of God: &#8220;Fear only the LORD your God, and he will rescue you from all your enemies.&#8221; This promise&#8212;exclusive covenant loyalty resulting in divine protection&#8212;is the positive form of the covenant. The NT presents Christ as the one who provides the ultimate rescue: not from political enemies but from sin and death themselves (Matt 1:21; 1 Cor 15:55&#8211;57). The &#8220;rescue from all your enemies&#8221; finds its fullest expression in the resurrection and the new creation.</p>',
"40": '<p>The shadow: &#8220;But they would not listen; they kept to their old ways.&#8221; The refusal to hear is the persistent covenant-breaking act in Kings. The prophets spoke, God warned through the narrative of events, and yet the people would not hear. The NT presents the same diagnostic: &#8220;Whoever has ears, let them hear&#8221; (Matt 13:9) is Christ&#8217;s repeated call. The hardened heart that would not listen requires the transforming work of the Spirit (Ezek 36:27) to hear and obey&#8212;what Christ sends at Pentecost.</p>',
"41": '<p>The shadow: &#8220;So these peoples worshiped the LORD but also served their own idols. Their children and grandchildren do the same today.&#8221; The intergenerational persistence of syncretism&#8212;passing from generation to generation&#8212;is the final note of the chapter and the final description of Samaritan religion. This is the condition Jesus enters in John 4: centuries of people drinking from the wrong wells. He offers living water that ends thirst permanently (John 4:13&#8211;14)&#8212;the answer to every generation&#8217;s divided worship.</p>'
}
}

def main():
    out_path = "data/commentary/mkt-christ/2kings.json"
    existing = load_comm(out_path)
    before = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    after = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    save_comm(out_path, existing)
    added = after - before
    print(f"  wrote {out_path}")
    for c in ['15','16','17']:
        print(f"  ch{c}: {len(existing.get(c,{}))} entries")
    print(f"2kings mkt-christ ch15-17 fill: added {added} verses")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
